    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_001/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly compares PALS (which implements mPLAGE) against ORA and GSEA for robustness to noise and missing data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Does PALS demonstrate greater robustness to noise and missing peaks in metabolomics peak data compared to ORA and GSEA methods?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:15.815193+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_001/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Here, we present PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring), a Python library, command line tool, and Web application that performs the ranking of significantly changing metabolite sets over different experimental conditions.",
      "asbval:note": "PALS is the primary tool developed and evaluated in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:15.815193+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_001/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "At level 0% (where no additional decoy features are present), both ORA and mPLAGE perform well, returning median p-values of 2\u00d710\u22126 and 0.0049, respectively. GSEA performs less well with median p-value of 0.0578... At level 100%, both ORA and mPLAGE perform well even when there are as many decoy features as there are actually changing features, returning median p-values of 0.0083 and 0.0003 for mPLAGE and ORA, respectively. At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper presents detailed tabular and numerical comparisons of methods across noise levels (0%, 25%, 50%, 100%, 250%, 500%, 1000% decoy features).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Robustness comparison table (methods \u00d7 noise-level \u00d7 robustness-metric)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:15.815193+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_001/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Assessing changes to the p-values of the true changing pathways with higher number of decoy features reveals that increasing the number of decoy features generally produces higher p-values (Figure 1)... Inspection of individual significant pathways of varying sizes (Figure 2) revealed that the mean p-values returned by all methods generally decreases with an increasing number of changing features in a pathway... Finally, F1 score performance was evaluated... Using this metric, it could be seen that the performance of ORA and mPLAGE were roughly similar using 0\u2013100% levels of non-changing features (Figure 3).",
      "asbval:note": "The paper includes multiple figures (Figures 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6) visualizing robustness metrics across methods and noise levels.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Robustness metric visualization (e.g., line plot or heatmap showing PALS vs. ORA vs. GSEA performance under noise)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:15.815193+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card focuses on 'noise and missing peaks' but the paper distinguishes between two separate robustness experiments: (1) decoy/noisy features added to pathways, and (2) missing features randomly removed. Both are addressed in the paper but represent distinct perturbation types.",
        "The card's framing of 'missing peaks' aligns with the paper's 'missing features' terminology, which is appropriate for untargeted metabolomics.",
        "The research question is well-centered on the paper's core contribution: demonstrating mPLAGE/PALS robustness superiority over ORA and GSEA."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:15.815193+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The initial activity level (AL) score for a set of metabolites is computed using singular value decomposition (SVD) following the method described for PLAGE [7], and adapted for metabolomics data (mPLAGE)... Given an intensity matrix X for a group of metabolites (where rows are the features annotated with formulae and columns are the samples in the data set), the decomposition of X can be written as X=U\u03a3V where columns in U are the orthonormal left singular vectors representing \"metacompounds\", \u03a3 contains the diagonal matrix of singular values arranged in descending order, and rows in V are the right singular vectors representing the contribution of the corresponding metacompounds to each sample. The AL score in a sample j is given by vj, where v is the first row in V, which is a vector of coefficients representing the activity levels of the first metacompound in U (having the largest singular value) across samples.",
      "asbval:note": "The research question is directly addressed in the paper's detailed description of the mPLAGE method (PLAGE adapted for metabolomics), which explains how intensity matrices are decomposed via SVD to produce activity level scores.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does the PLAGE decomposition method in PALS convert a metabolite intensity matrix and pathway database into quantitative pathway activity level scores?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:31.789845+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
