    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_003/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the MF analysis, Global Natural Products Social Molecular Networking (GNPS) example data were taken from the American Gut Project [26]. From this, a subset of data was chosen from volunteers who had consumed different amounts of plant-based food. In this study, 35 significantly changing MFs (p-value \u2264 0.05) containing 10 or more molecules were found between the case (eating >30 plant-based foods a week) and control (<10 plant-based foods a week) groups.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper demonstrates PLAGE decomposition applied to MFs with activity scores (p-values) computed for each family across samples.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Activity score matrix decomposed by PLAGE for Molecular Families (samples \u00d7 families with PLAGE scores)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:44.410982+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_003/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To anaylse Mass2Motifs, a data set from the GNPS-MS2LDA workflow, consisting of 70 Rhamnacea species from two clades and various genera, was used [4]. In the original study, 25 Mass2Motifs were manually characterized and their distribution over the Rhamnaceae clades examined. The statistical significance of the results were easily obtained using PALS, whereas all previous efforts relied on manual interpretation.",
      "asbval:note": "PALS applies mPLAGE to Mass2Motifs, producing activity scores (p-values) for each motif across samples.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Activity score matrix decomposed by PLAGE for Mass2Motifs (samples \u00d7 motifs with PLAGE scores)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:44.410982+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_003/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper demonstrates robustness of mPLAGE to noise and missing data, but the robustness evaluation (synthetic and real data experiments) is primarily conducted on pathway data, not specifically on non-pathway groupings (MFs and Mass2Motifs). The non-pathway analysis section (2.3) does not include explicit robustness comparisons with noise/missing data perturbations.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Comparative results demonstrating robustness of non-pathway decomposition to noise and missing peaks",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:44.410982+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_003/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The modularity of PALS also means it is not limited to pathways, and any user-defined grouping of features (representing metabolite sets) can be readily analysed. This is demonstrated by assessing the activity levels of metabolite sets grouped by similarity of fragmentation spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly confirms that mPLAGE generalises to non-pathway metabolite groupings and demonstrates this with MF and Mass2Motif analyses.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Results presentation confirming PLAGE generalisation to non-pathway metabolite groupings",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:44.410982+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_003/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card's expected output on 'robustness of non-pathway decomposition to noise and missing peaks' is partially supported: the paper demonstrates mPLAGE robustness to noise and missing data, but the systematic robustness evaluation (with synthetic data perturbations and F1 score metrics) is applied primarily to pathway data. The non-pathway analysis (Section 2.3) presents results but does not include the same level of robustness benchmarking against noise/missing features as the pathway analysis does."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 1,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:32:44.410982+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_1471_2105_6_225__task_004/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In this experiment, an increasing number of decoy features were added to the seven pathways comprised of significantly changing features. This scenario reflects the case of attempting to find pathways, or sets of metabolites, with high activity levels when the number of significantly changing metabolites are small compared to noisy data, nonchanging or wrongly annotated metabolites... Additionally, the effect of introducing an increasing number of missing features from the pathways was explored.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper tests robustness to decoy (noise) features and missing features separately, but does NOT explicitly test combined Gaussian noise + peak removal perturbations or rank-order stability metrics (Spearman/Kendall correlation). Paper evaluates p-value changes and F1 scores, not rank-order correlation or top-K retention.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_004",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does the rank-order stability of top-scoring pathways in PALS degrade as Gaussian noise and random peak removal increase in severity across a metabolomics dataset?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:33:05.423838+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
