      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-activity-scoring/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Metabolites, pathways, and the mapping of metabolites to pathways are obtained in PALS by querying from a local copy of the KEGG database [29] or by querying a Reactome instance running on top of a local Neo4j graph database... Reactome is regularly updated, with the entire database available from the Reactome website",
      "asbval:note": "Reactome confirmed as pathway database with Neo4j backend; local (offline) mode confirmed. Online mode implied by 'regularly updated' and website reference.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-activity-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Reactome - Pathway database for metabolite set definition; supports online (Neo4j server) and offline modes",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:15.530438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-activity-scoring/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "As an option for data normalisation, the intensity matrix is subsequently transformed to log space and standardised using the preprocessing module in Scipy [27] such that each factor has a zero mean and unit variance across the samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms log transformation and standardization (zero mean, unit variance). However, paper does not explicitly mention ChEBI IDs; only KEGG and Reactome are named as pathway databases. KEGG is confirmed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-activity-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "log2-transformed, standardized peak intensity matrices with metabolite annotations (peak ID \u2192 KEGG/ChEBI IDs)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:15.530438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-activity-scoring/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PALS is designed to look at how metabolic pathways or other groups of metabolites change between different experimental conditions. It achieves this by decomposing peak intensities into latent factors corresponding to observed metabolic changes (activities).",
      "asbval:note": "Core functionality confirmed: testing co-variation of peaks within pathways and spectral groupings.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-activity-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "test whether groups of peaks co-vary systematically within known pathways or spectral groupings",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:15.530438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-activity-scoring/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A comparison of mPLAGE with two other commonly used methods (overrepresentation analysis (ORA) and gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA)) is also given and reveals that mPLAGE is more robust to missing features and noisy data than the alternatives.",
      "asbval:note": "Robustness comparison confirmed across multiple passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-activity-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "higher robustness than ORA or GSEA approaches",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:15.530438+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The initial activity level (AL) score for a set of metabolites is computed using singular value decomposition (SVD) following the method described for PLAGE [7], and adapted for metabolomics data (mPLAGE)... Given an intensity matrix X for a group of metabolites (where rows are the features annotated with formulae and columns are the samples in the data set), the decomposition of X can be written as X=U\u03a3V... The AL score in a sample j is given by vj, where v is the first row in V, which is a vector of coefficients representing the activity levels of the first metacompound in U (having the largest singular value) across samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: SVD decomposition of metabolite intensity matrices to extract activity level scores for metabolite sets including pathways, molecular families, and Mass2Motifs.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Decompose metabolite intensity data across predefined metabolite sets (pathways, molecular families, or mass2motifs) using singular value decomposition (SVD) to extract pathway activity level scores that rank biological processes by their magnitude and statistical significance.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data... At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared... mPLAGE is generally more robust to missing features than the alternative methods tested.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: mPLAGE (PLAGE for metabolomics) is demonstrated to be more robust to noise and missing data than ORA and GSEA.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This approach is more robust to noise and missing peaks than enrichment-based alternatives (ORA, GSEA), making it suitable for metabolomics data with sparse or noisy measurements.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Here, we present PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring), a Python library, command line tool, and Web application that performs the ranking of significantly changing metabolite sets over different experimental conditions.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: PALS is the primary tool implementing metabolite-set decomposition and ranking.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PALS also presents a comprehensive Python-based library that can be easily run in several modes: as a standalone tool, an interactive Web application (PALS Viewer), or a Python library.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: PALS Viewer is the web-based interface for PALS.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS Viewer",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The performance of mPLAGE was compared to widely used overrepresentation (ORA) analysis and gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) methods... These alternative methods, used for benchmarking experiments, are included in the PALS Python library, allowing all methods to be compared utilising the same database query codes and retrieving identical pathways from KEGG and Reactome.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: ORA is included in PALS for comparison with mPLAGE.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ORA (Over-Representation Analysis)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The performance of mPLAGE was compared to widely used overrepresentation (ORA) analysis and gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) methods... These alternative methods, used for benchmarking experiments, are included in the PALS Python library, allowing all methods to be compared utilising the same database query codes and retrieving identical pathways from KEGG and Reactome.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: GSEA is included in PALS for comparison with mPLAGE.",
