    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To analyse both MFs and Mass2Motifs, Python code is provided in PALS to retrieve information on the metabolite sets as well as the peak intensity table from GNPS (Figure 7B)... Both FBMN and MS2LDA are accessible as workflows from Global Natural Products Social Molecular Networking (GNPS, [2]), which provides community resources to run large-scale molecular networking and annotations of spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: GNPS is the source of molecular family and Mass2Motif data that can be analyzed in PALS.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "GNPS (Global Natural Products Social Molecular Networking)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The second method employs a topic-modelling approach (MS2LDA, [5]) to generate groups of peaks (called Mass2Motifs) based on the shared presence of fragment and neutral loss features in their fragmentation spectra. Both FBMN and MS2LDA are accessible as workflows from Global Natural Products Social Molecular Networking (GNPS, [2]).",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: MS2LDA is used to generate Mass2Motifs that can be analyzed as metabolite sets in PALS.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "MS2LDA",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring), a Python library, command line tool, and Web application that performs the ranking of significantly changing metabolite sets over different experimental conditions... Metabolites, pathways, and the mapping of metabolites to pathways are obtained in PALS by querying from a local copy of the KEGG database [29] or by querying a Reactome instance running on top of a local Neo4j graph database... The initial activity level (AL) score for a set of metabolites is computed using singular value decomposition (SVD)...",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: PALS performs database queries, PLAGE decomposition (mPLAGE), and ranking of metabolite sets.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[PALS].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Complete implementation of metabolite-set decomposition and ranking; performs database queries, PLAGE decomposition, and result presentation",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To facilitate the use of the activity analysis described in this project, PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring) software was developed. PALS can be run either as a standalone tool, imported as a Python library, or used via a Web interface allowing users with a wide range of expertise and requirements to use it... To assist beginners, a Web interface is provided to run PALS in an intuitive and user-friendly manner",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: PALS Viewer is the web interface for running PALS and inspecting results.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[PALS Viewer].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Web-based interface for running PALS and inspecting ranked pathway results; enables visualization of activity levels and comparison across samples",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/010",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "ORA approaches rely on testing for the presence or absence of significantly changing genes in a pathway, using statistical significance tests... These alternative methods, used for benchmarking experiments, are included in the PALS Python library... At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared.",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: ORA is included in PALS for comparison and is less robust than mPLAGE to noise and missing data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[ORA].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Alternative pathway ranking method included in PALS for comparison; does not use decomposition and is more sensitive to noise and missing peaks",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/011",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "FCS methods, which include gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) [6] use statistical approaches to identify gene sets that are significantly enriched or depleted in the pathway... These alternative methods, used for benchmarking experiments, are included in the PALS Python library... GSEA performs worst among the three methods tested, particularly showing its sensitivity to nonchanging or decoy features.",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: GSEA is included in PALS for comparison and is more sensitive to noise and missing data than mPLAGE.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[GSEA].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Alternative pathway ranking method included in PALS for comparison; does not use decomposition and is more sensitive to noise and missing peaks",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:37:34.027278+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-analysis/012",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the MF analysis, Global Natural Products Social Molecular Networking (GNPS) example data were taken from the American Gut Project [26]... To analyse both MFs and Mass2Motifs, Python code is provided in PALS to retrieve information on the metabolite sets as well as the peak intensity table from GNPS (Figure 7B).",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: GNPS provides molecular family data that PALS can analyze.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[GNPS].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Source of molecular family definitions that can be analyzed as metabolite sets in PALS",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
