    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Python code is provided in PALS to retrieve information on the metabolite sets as well as the peak intensity table from GNPS... To analyse both MFs and Mass2Motifs, Python code is provided in PALS to retrieve information on the metabolite sets... feature and annotation CSV files are input on the command line along with experimental design parameters",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes CSV input for features and annotations, and retrieval of metabolite set data from GNPS, but does not explicitly describe user-uploaded custom metabolite set file parsing with validation against database schema. The paper focuses on three shipped set types (pathways from KEGG/Reactome, MFs from GNPS, Mass2Motifs from GNPS) rather than generic user-uploaded custom sets.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Parse user-uploaded metabolite set files (CSV or JSON format) to extract metabolite identifiers and set membership, then validate the structure and identifiers against the PALS database schema before downstream decomposition analysis.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:15.747514+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The decomposition approach employed by mPLAGE is not limited to the analysis of pathways. In fact, any user-defined grouping of features, where each metabolite set can be represented as the intensity matrix X (features vs. samples), can be used for for activity level decomposition.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper states that mPLAGE can accept any user-defined grouping of features, but does not describe a file parsing/validation workflow for custom user-uploaded sets. The extensibility is conceptual rather than operationalized via a documented parsing interface.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill enables extensibility of pathway activity scoring to custom metabolite groupings beyond the three shipped set types (pathways, Molecular Families, and Mass2Motifs).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:15.747514+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "any user-defined grouping of features, where each metabolite set can be represented as the intensity matrix X (features vs. samples), can be used for for activity level decomposition",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms that user-defined metabolite sets can be analyzed, but does not explicitly document CSV or JSON file format specifications for user-uploaded custom sets, nor validation workflows.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When a user has prepared a custom collection of metabolite sets (e.g., from spectral fragmentation clustering, literature curation, or domain-specific grouping) in CSV or JSON format and wants to score their activity levels using PALS",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:15.747514+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Metabolites, pathways, and the mapping of metabolites to pathways are obtained in PALS by querying from a local copy of the KEGG database [29] or by querying a Reactome instance... Features are annotated as compound formulae and these are linked to the metabolites in the metabolite set/pathway of interest.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes validation/mapping of features to pathways via KEGG and Reactome, but does not explicitly describe a validation workflow for user-uploaded custom metabolite sets against ChEBI or other external databases.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Metabolite identifiers and set membership must be validated against KEGG, ChEBI, or other database schemas before feeding into the PLAGE decomposition pipeline.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:15.747514+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for PALS | role: tool] Pathway Activity Level Scoring (PALS), a comprehensive and modular Python tool for metabolite set enrichment. PALS is designed to look at how metabolic pathways or other groups of metabolites change between different experimental conditions.",
      "asbval:note": "PALS is confirmed as the primary tool for metabolite set activity scoring via mPLAGE decomposition.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS \u2014 Accepts validated metabolite sets as input to PLAGE decomposition for activity scoring",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:15.747514+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To facilitate the use of the activity analysis described in this project, PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring) software was developed. PALS can be run either as a standalone tool, imported as a Python library, or used via a Web interface allowing users with a wide range of expertise and requirements to use it... To assist beginners, a Web interface is provided to run PALS in an intuitive and user-friendly manner",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms PALS has a Web interface (PALS Viewer) for user-friendly display of results.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-set-file-parsing-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS Viewer \u2014 Web interface that displays parsed and scored results from custom metabolite sets in a user-friendly tabular format",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:15.747514+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolomics-noise-perturbation-simulation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To assess the robustness of mPLAGE, benchmarking experiments were performed. Initially, these experiments were performed using synthetic data... Seven synthetic pathways were constructed with significant changes... To mimic the inclusion of formulae that arise due to incorrect identification/annotation, decoy features were generated using a normal distribution... To simulate missing features, which often occurs in real metabolomics data, features were also randomly removed from pathways with a uniform probability of 0.2.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses decoy features (noise simulation) and random removal (peak dropout) to assess robustness of mPLAGE, ORA, and GSEA.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolomics-noise-perturbation-simulation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Systematically degrade a metabolomics peak intensity matrix with controlled levels of Gaussian noise and random peak dropout to assess the robustness of pathway ranking algorithms.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:32.276939+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolomics-noise-perturbation-simulation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data.",
