    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To assess the robustness of mPLAGE, benchmarking experiments were performed. Initially, these experiments were performed using synthetic data... To simulate missing features, which often occurs in real metabolomics data, features were also randomly removed from pathways with a uniform probability of 0.2... Additionally, the effect of introducing an increasing number of missing features from the pathways was explored... The level of decoy features was fixed to 100%... The percentage of features randomly missing from the data was indicated by p, and this value was varied from 20%, 40%, 60%, and 80% of the full data set.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly performs controlled introduction of missing features and decoy (noise) features at varying levels to benchmark robustness.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Systematically introduce controlled levels of missing peaks and noise artifacts into omics intensity matrices to assess method robustness and generalization.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data... For all methods, it can be noted that the F1 score decreases as the proportion of missing features increase... This suggests that it becomes harder for all tested methods to reconstruct the original pathway ranking results obtained from the full data when fewer input features are available.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper evaluates ranking stability (via F1 score, precision, recall) under missing data and noise conditions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "validates whether pathway analysis methods maintain ranking stability and effect size preservation under realistic data degradation scenarios common in metabolomics",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The performance of mPLAGE was compared to widely used overrepresentation (ORA) analysis and gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) methods... A comparison of mPLAGE with two other commonly used methods (overrepresentation analysis (ORA) and gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA)) is also given and reveals that mPLAGE is more robust to missing features and noisy data than the alternatives.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly compares three methods: mPLAGE, ORA, and GSEA.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "comparing the robustness of multiple pathway ranking methods (e.g., PLAGE, ORA, GSEA)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To mimic the inclusion of formulae that arise due to incorrect identification/annotation, decoy features were generated using a normal distribution... To simulate missing features, which often occurs in real metabolomics data, features were also randomly removed from pathways with a uniform probability of 0.2.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper addresses annotation uncertainty (via decoy features) and missing features (peak dropout), but does not explicitly address 'instrumental noise' as a separate category\u2014noise is simulated via decoy features generated from normal distribution.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "peak dropout, instrumental noise, or annotation uncertainty",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "As an option for data normalisation, the intensity matrix is subsequently transformed to log space and standardised using the preprocessing module in Scipy [27] such that each factor has a zero mean and unit variance across the samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes log transformation and standardization as preprocessing step in PALS workflow.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input intensity data have not been log-2 transformed and standardized (zero mean, unit variance)\u2014apply preprocessing first",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The modularity of PALS also means it is not limited to pathways, and any user-defined grouping of features (representing metabolite sets) can be readily analysed... The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper emphasizes multi-method comparison as core design principle.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Comparing only a single pathway analysis method; this skill is designed for benchmarking across multiple methods",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Inspection of individual significant pathways of varying sizes (Figure 2) revealed that the mean p-values returned by all methods generally decreases with an increasing number of changing features in a pathway... As a result of the small number of metabolites in the pathway, all methods struggle to correctly identify pathways Two and Four as significantly changing at any level of added decoy features and generally perform better on the larger pathways Twenty, Forty, and Eighty.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates that method performance depends on pathway/metabolite set size; small sets are harder to detect.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Peak annotations are missing or sparse; method comparison requires sufficient metabolite set members",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Here, we present PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring), a Python library, command line tool, and Web application that performs the ranking of significantly changing metabolite sets over different experimental conditions. The main algorithm in PALS is based on the pathway level analysis of gene expression (PLAGE) factorisation method and is denoted as mPLAGE (PLAGE for metabolomics).",
      "asbval:note": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for PALS | role: primary pathway analysis tool]",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring) \u2014 Computes pathway activity scores via PLAGE decomposition; primary target method for robustness comparison",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:38:48.111121+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/missing-data-simulation-in-omics/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "ORA approaches rely on testing for the presence or absence of significantly changing genes in a pathway, using statistical significance tests... The performance of mPLAGE was compared to widely used overrepresentation (ORA) analysis and gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) methods... These alternative methods, used for benchmarking experiments, are included in the PALS Python library, allowing all methods to be compared utilising the same database query codes and retrieving identical pathways from KEGG and Reactome.",
      "asbval:note": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for ORA | role: benchmarking method]",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "missing-data-simulation-in-omics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ORA (Over-Representation Analysis) \u2014 Baseline pathway ranking method using hypergeometric test; included in PALS for benchmarking against PLAGE",
