    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-family-grouping-analysis/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To demonstrate the analysis of other types of metabolite sets, PALS was used to assess the activity levels of potentially unknown metabolites grouped into molecular families (MFs) through their fragmentation spectral similarities, and into Mass2Motifs based on shared fragment and neutral loss features.",
      "asbval:note": "Core claim fully supported by passage 7, which explicitly describes PALS application to MFs and Mass2Motifs.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-family-grouping-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply PALS decomposition (PLAGE method) to metabolite groupings from spectral clustering (Molecular Families from GNPS, Mass2Motifs from MS2LDA) to compute activity scores and identify significantly changing metabolite groups across experimental conditions.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:14.946510+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-family-grouping-analysis/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The modularity of PALS also means it is not limited to pathways, and any user-defined grouping of features (representing metabolite sets) can be readily analysed. This is demonstrated by assessing the activity levels of metabolite sets grouped by similarity of fragmentation spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "Passage 4 confirms PALS modularity and extension beyond pathways to spectral groupings.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-family-grouping-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This extends classical pathway-based analysis to spectral phenotypes, which are often more robust to annotation uncertainty in untargeted metabolomics.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:14.946510+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-family-grouping-analysis/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we present PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring), a Python library, command line tool, and Web application that performs the ranking of significantly changing metabolite sets over different experimental conditions. The main algorithm in PALS is based on the pathway level analysis of gene expression (PLAGE) factorisation method and is denoted as mPLAGE (PLAGE for metabolomics).",
      "asbval:note": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for PALS | role: core tool]. Passage 2 confirms PALS as Python library/CLI/web app with mPLAGE algorithm.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-family-grouping-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring) \u2014 Core decomposition and activity scoring engine; performs PLAGE SVD-based decomposition on any metabolite grouping",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:14.946510+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-family-grouping-analysis/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the MF analysis, Global Natural Products Social Molecular Networking (GNPS) example data were taken from the American Gut Project. ... To analyse both MFs and Mass2Motifs, Python code is provided in PALS to retrieve information on the metabolite sets as well as the peak intensity table from GNPS",
      "asbval:note": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for GNPS | role: source of MF data]. Passage 7 confirms GNPS as source of Molecular Family groupings.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-family-grouping-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "GNPS (Global Natural Products Social Molecular Networking) \u2014 Source of Molecular Family spectral groupings",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:14.946510+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-family-grouping-analysis/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To anaylse Mass2Motifs, a data set from the GNPS-MS2LDA workflow, consisting of 70 Rhamnacea species from two clades and various genera, was used. ... the second method employs a topic-modelling approach (MS2LDA, [5]) to generate groups of peaks (called Mass2Motifs) based on the shared presence of fragment and neutral loss features in their fragmentation spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for MS2LDA | role: source of Mass2Motif data]. Passage 7 confirms MS2LDA generates Mass2Motifs.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-family-grouping-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "MS2LDA (Mass2Motif Latent Dirichlet Allocation) \u2014 Source of Mass2Motif spectral motif groupings",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:14.946510+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-family-grouping-analysis/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PALS can be run either as a standalone tool, imported as a Python library, or used via a Web interface allowing users with a wide range of expertise and requirements to use it. ... To assist beginners, a Web interface is provided to run PALS in an intuitive and user-friendly manner",
      "asbval:note": "Passage 9 confirms web interface availability; passage 10 mentions 'PALS Viewer' by name as interactive web application.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
