      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/non-pathway-metabolite-classification/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To anaylse Mass2Motifs, a data set from the GNPS-MS2LDA workflow, consisting of 70 Rhamnacea species from two clades and various genera, was used... The second method employs a topic-modelling approach (MS2LDA, [5]) to generate groups of peaks (called Mass2Motifs) based on the shared presence of fragment and neutral loss features in their fragmentation spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "MS2LDA confirmed as source of Mass2Motifs; PALS can import and analyze them.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "non-pathway-metabolite-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "MS2LDA \u2014 Source of Mass2Motif groupings; PALS can import and rank Mass2Motifs as metabolite sets.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:35.662286+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/non-pathway-metabolite-classification/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PALS is designed to look at how metabolic pathways or other groups of metabolites change between different experimental conditions. It achieves this by decomposing peak intensities into latent factors corresponding to observed metabolic changes (activities).",
      "asbval:note": "Scope directly supported; paper describes PALS as designed for ranking metabolite sets across experimental conditions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "non-pathway-metabolite-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have metabolomics intensity data with peak annotations, and you want to rank and prioritize metabolite groupings (Molecular Families, Mass2Motifs, or other non-pathway metabolite sets) by their activity levels across experimental contrasts.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:35.662286+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/non-pathway-metabolite-classification/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To demonstrate the analysis of other types of metabolite sets, PALS was used to assess the activity levels of potentially unknown metabolites grouped into molecular families (MFs) through their fragmentation spectral similarities, and into Mass2Motifs based on shared fragment and neutral loss features.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly demonstrates PALS use for spectral clustering outputs (MFs, Mass2Motifs) as alternative to pathway-based analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "non-pathway-metabolite-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this when pathway databases are unavailable, inapplicable, or when you want to leverage spectral clustering outputs (GNPS or MS2LDA) instead of curated pathway resources.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:35.662286+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The initial activity level (AL) score for a set of metabolites is computed using singular value decomposition (SVD) following the method described for PLAGE [7], and adapted for metabolomics data (mPLAGE)... Given an intensity matrix X for a group of metabolites (where rows are the features annotated with formulae and columns are the samples in the data set), the decomposition of X can be written as X=U\u03a3V",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: SVD decomposition of intensity matrices for metabolite groups is the core method.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PLAGE (Pathway Level Analysis using Gene Expression) decomposes peak intensity or gene expression matrices into pathway activity scores by applying singular value decomposition to metabolite or gene groups within curated pathways.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:50.682697+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared... mPLAGE is generally more robust to missing features than the alternative methods tested. These results were also supported by the F1 score performance (Figure 5), where mPLAGE generally performed best even when large numbers of features were missing from the data.",
      "asbval:note": "Direct evidence: mPLAGE (PLAGE for metabolomics) outperforms ORA and GSEA on robustness to noise and missing data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This rank-based approach is more robust to noise and missing peaks than alternatives like ORA and GSEA",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:50.682697+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "As an option for data normalisation, the intensity matrix is subsequently transformed to log space and standardised using the preprocessing module in Scipy [27] such that each factor has a zero mean and unit variance across the samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: log transformation and standardization are described as preprocessing steps.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have a log2-transformed, standardized peak intensity matrix (rows = metabolite features, columns = samples)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:50.682697+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Metabolites, pathways, and the mapping of metabolites to pathways are obtained in PALS by querying from a local copy of the KEGG database [29] or by querying a Reactome instance running on top of a local Neo4j graph database",
      "asbval:note": "Verbatim match: KEGG and Reactome are explicitly named as pathway databases used by PALS.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "with compound annotations mapped to curated pathway databases (KEGG, Reactome, or custom metabolite sets)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:50.682697+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The results here suggest that even when there are many missing features, mPLAGE is able to recover more original pathways in the full data using a small fraction of the features present in the original peak data, returning a higher number of true positives and fewer false positives and false negatives.",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: the paper demonstrates that mPLAGE ranks pathways by activity while tolerating missing features.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-activity-decomposition-via-plage",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "you need to rank pathways by their activity level while tolerating missing peaks or detection noise",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:39:50.682697+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
