    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-level-activity-scoring/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "As input to activity level decomposition using mPLAGE (see Section 3.4), a peak intensity matrix X is constructed for each metabolite set... Metabolites, pathways, and the mapping of metabolites to pathways are obtained in PALS by querying from a local copy of the KEGG database [29] or by querying a Reactome instance",
      "asbval:note": "Scope description aligns with paper's description of input requirements and KEGG/Reactome database integration.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-level-activity-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have a metabolite intensity matrix (samples \u00d7 metabolites) with assigned annotations (peak IDs mapped to KEGG or ChEBI compound IDs), a metabolic pathway database, and need to rank pathways by activity level",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:40:28.223500+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-level-activity-scoring/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "FCS methods, which include gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) [6] use statistical approaches to identify gene sets that are significantly enriched or depleted in the pathway... One such FCS method is pathway level analysis of gene expression (PLAGE) [7], which performs singular value decomposition (SVD) to compute an activity value from expression data in a sample... the PLAGE method does not discriminate between upward or downward activity, meaning that both increases and decreases in gene expression contribute to the activity of a pathway.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper emphasizes PLAGE's quantitative approach and robustness to noise/missing data, supporting the scope claim about preserving intensity information.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-level-activity-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this when peaks exhibit high noise or sparse coverage, as PLAGE preserves quantitative intensity information rather than binarizing presence/absence.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:40:28.223500+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-rank-stability-assessment/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To assess the robustness of mPLAGE, benchmarking experiments were performed... To mimic the inclusion of formulae that arise due to incorrect identification/annotation, decoy features were generated using a normal distribution... To simulate missing features, which often occurs in real metabolomics data, features were also randomly removed from pathways with a uniform probability of 0.2.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly tests robustness via synthetic data with decoy features (noise proxy) and random feature removal (dropout). Gaussian distribution used for decoy generation; uniform probability for missing features.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-rank-stability-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Quantify the robustness of pathway activity rankings under realistic perturbations (Gaussian noise and random peak dropout)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:40:54.869863+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-rank-stability-assessment/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Assuming that a particular pathway ranking Pm returned by a method m on the complete data will be better than the ones obtained from the reduced data (with missing features), results from the complete data could be used as the true answers for evaluation.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper compares pathway rankings on complete vs. degraded (missing feature) data to assess stability and recovery of original rankings.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-rank-stability-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "validate that top-scoring pathways remain stable across degraded metabolomics data",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:40:54.869863+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-rank-stability-assessment/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates mPLAGE robustness to noise and missing data, core claim of the research question.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-rank-stability-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PALS pathway decomposition produces reliable discoveries despite the noise and missing peaks prevalent in mass spectrometry workflows",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:40:54.869863+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
