    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-ranking-and-prioritization/013",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The initial activity level (AL) score for a set of metabolites is computed using singular value decomposition (SVD) following the method described for PLAGE [7], and adapted for metabolomics data (mPLAGE).",
      "asbval:note": "SVD-based decomposition confirmed as core mechanism.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-ranking-and-prioritization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[PLAGE].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Decomposition method embedded in PALS that applies SVD to each pathway's metabolites to compute activity scores",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:41:14.661972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-ranking-and-prioritization/014",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared. ... For all pathways across all levels of added decoy features, mPLAGE returns lower p-values compared to ORA and GSEA.",
      "asbval:note": "mPLAGE shown to outperform ORA under noise conditions; ORA included in PALS for comparison.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-ranking-and-prioritization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[ORA].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Alternative pathway ranking method included in PALS for benchmarking; less robust to noise than PLAGE",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:41:14.661972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-ranking-and-prioritization/015",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared. ... GSEA performed worst among the three methods tested, particularly showing its sensitivity to nonchanging or decoy features.",
      "asbval:note": "GSEA explicitly shown to be most sensitive to noise; mPLAGE more robust.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-ranking-and-prioritization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[GSEA].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Alternative pathway ranking method included in PALS for benchmarking; less robust to noise than PLAGE",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:41:14.661972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/peak-removal-robustness-testing/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Additionally, the effect of introducing an increasing number of missing features from the pathways was explored. For this experiment, the level of decoy features was fixed to 100% in order to allow for an equal number of changing and nonchanging features. The percentage of features randomly missing from the data was indicated by p, and this value was varied from 20%, 40%, 60%, and 80% of the full data set... The results in Figure 4 show that as the number of missing features increases, mPLAGE consistently returns lower mean p-values with smaller variances than ORA or GSEA. This suggests that mPLAGE is generally more robust to missing features than the alternative methods tested.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper directly evaluates pathway ranking stability under progressive feature removal (peak dropout), comparing PLAGE/mPLAGE, ORA, and GSEA methods.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "peak-removal-robustness-testing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Assess the stability of pathway activity rankings under random peak dropout to validate that pathway scoring methods can tolerate missing metabolite identifications\u2014a common problem in metabolomics datasets.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:41:41.130565+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/peak-removal-robustness-testing/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Assuming that a particular pathway ranking Pm returned by a method m on the complete data will be better than the ones obtained from the reduced data (with missing features), results from the complete data could be used as the true answers for evaluation... This evaluation procedure was repeated 500 times.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly compares pathway rankings from complete data against reduced data with progressively removed features to assess stability.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "peak-removal-robustness-testing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill measures whether top-ranking pathways remain stable as peaks are progressively removed from the dataset.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:41:41.130565+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/peak-removal-robustness-testing/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for PALS | role: Primary method] Here, we present PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring), a Python library, command line tool, and Web application that performs the ranking of significantly changing metabolite sets over different experimental conditions.",
      "asbval:note": "PALS is the primary tool used throughout the paper for pathway activity level scoring and robustness testing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "peak-removal-robustness-testing",
