      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/principal-component-extraction-from-pathway-subsets/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The second method employs a topic-modelling approach (MS2LDA, [5]) to generate groups of peaks (called Mass2Motifs) based on the shared presence of fragment and neutral loss features in their fragmentation spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "MS2LDA is explicitly mentioned as source of Mass2Motifs that can be analyzed via PALS.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "principal-component-extraction-from-pathway-subsets",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "MS2LDA",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:02.159055+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/principal-component-extraction-from-pathway-subsets/010",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PALS is designed to look at how metabolic pathways or other groups of metabolites change between different experimental conditions. It achieves this by decomposing peak intensities into latent factors corresponding to observed metabolic changes (activities)... Database queries that map compounds to pathways are integrated into the system using either KEGG or Reactome databases.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes PALS as implementing all these functions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "principal-component-extraction-from-pathway-subsets",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "role: Complete implementation of PLAGE-based pathway decomposition; performs database queries, SVD-based PLAGE decomposition, normalization, ranking, and statistical significance computation",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:02.159055+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/principal-component-extraction-from-pathway-subsets/011",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To facilitate the use of the activity analysis described in this project, PALS (Pathway Activity Level Scoring) software was developed. PALS can be run either as a standalone tool, imported as a Python library, or used via a Web interface allowing users with a wide range of expertise and requirements to use it.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes PALS Viewer as web interface for running PALS and analyzing results.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "principal-component-extraction-from-pathway-subsets",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "role: Web-based interactive interface for running PALS, analyzing pathway ranking results, and inspecting significantly changing pathways",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:02.159055+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rank-order-correlation-analysis/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values... At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper evaluates robustness to noise and missing features using precision, recall, and F1 scores\u2014NOT rank-order correlations (Spearman's rho or Kendall's tau). The paper compares pathway rankings via p-value thresholds and F1 scores, not rank-order correlation metrics. The functional goal (robustness validation under perturbation) is present, but the specific statistical method (rank-order correlation) is not used.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "rank-order-correlation-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Quantify the stability of pathway activity rankings under perturbation (noise and missing peaks) by computing rank-order correlations (Spearman's rho or Kendall's tau) between baseline and perturbed pathway scores.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:21.890089+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rank-order-correlation-analysis/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments... The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly validates robustness of pathway ranking methods under degraded data quality (noise and missing features).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "rank-order-correlation-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill validates the robustness of pathway ranking methods in metabolomics by measuring how ranking order degrades as data quality decreases.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:21.890089+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rank-order-correlation-analysis/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To mimic the inclusion of formulae that arise due to incorrect identification/annotation, decoy features were generated using a normal distribution... To simulate missing features, which often occurs in real metabolomics data, features were also randomly removed from pathways with a uniform probability of 0.2.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses normal distribution for decoy features and uniform random removal for missing features. The claim specifies 'Gaussian noise' and 'random peak dropout', which align functionally but the paper does not explicitly label the decoy generation as 'Gaussian noise'\u2014it is described as 'normal distribution' for decoy features. Missing feature simulation matches 'random peak dropout'.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "rank-order-correlation-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have run a pathway ranking method (such as PALS/PLAGE) on clean metabolomics data and wish to assess how sensitive the resulting pathway activity rankings are to realistic data quality issues\u2014specifically Gaussian noise and random peak dropout",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:21.890089+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/rank-order-correlation-analysis/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
