      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/robustness-analysis-under-perturbation/010",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To assess the robustness of mPLAGE, benchmarking experiments were performed... The performance of mPLAGE was compared to widely used overrepresentation (ORA) analysis and gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) methods... This scenario reflects the case of attempting to find pathways, or sets of metabolites, with high activity levels when the number of significantly changing metabolites are small compared to noisy data, nonchanging or wrongly annotated metabolites.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates exactly this use case: comparing multiple methods (mPLAGE/PALS, ORA, GSEA) on metabolomics data with intentional data corruption (decoy features, missing features).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "robustness-analysis-under-perturbation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have completed pathway analysis using multiple competing methods (e.g., PALS, ORA, GSEA) on a metabolomics peak intensity dataset and need to verify that ranking results remain stable when input data is intentionally corrupted.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:42.298868+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/singular-value-decomposition-metabolomics/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The initial activity level (AL) score for a set of metabolites is computed using singular value decomposition (SVD) following the method described for PLAGE [7], and adapted for metabolomics data (mPLAGE)... The AL score in a sample j is given by vj, where v is the first row in V, which is a vector of coefficients representing the activity levels of the first metacompound in U (having the largest singular value) across samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Exact match: SVD applied to intensity matrix, first singular vector extracted as activity score.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "singular-value-decomposition-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply singular value decomposition (SVD) to metabolite intensity subsets within defined pathways to extract the first principal component as a pathway activity score.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:58.784769+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/singular-value-decomposition-metabolomics/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The robustness of mPLAGE was evaluated on both synthetic and real data experiments and compared to both ORA and GSEA methods. The results demonstrated that the mPLAGE method is robust to noise and missing values, which is particularly important for metabolomics data... At higher levels (250%, 500%, and 1000%), GSEA appears most sensitive to the perturbation, while mPLAGE performs best amongst the methods compared.",
      "asbval:note": "Robustness claim directly supported by synthetic and real data benchmarking.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "singular-value-decomposition-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This decomposition-based approach is more robust to noise and missing peaks than ORA and GSEA methods",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:58.784769+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/singular-value-decomposition-metabolomics/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "As an option for data normalisation, the intensity matrix is subsequently transformed to log space and standardised using the preprocessing module in Scipy [27] such that each factor has a zero mean and unit variance across the samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper specifies 'log space' (not explicitly 'log2'), zero mean, and unit variance. The card specifies 'log2-normalized' but the paper says 'log space' without specifying base. This is a minor semantic difference but functionally equivalent for the method.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo11020103",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "singular-value-decomposition-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
